        "rubricName": "Motivational Interviewing — MITI Global Ratings (MI Fidelity)",
        "content": "## MITI 4.2.1 Global Ratings — MI fidelity on five global dimensions\nEach dimension scored 1–5 as a single holistic judgment. Total 18/25 (0 dimensions excluded).\n\n## Scorecard\n| Domain | Score |\n| --- | --- |\n| Cultivating Change Talk | 3/5 · Good |\n| Softening Sustain Talk | 4/5 · Very good |\n| Partnership | 4/5 · Very good |\n| Empathy | 4/5 · Very good |\n| MI core skills (OARS) | 3/5 · Good |\n| **Total** | **18/25** |\n\n### Cultivating Change Talk — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** \"so what it actually does is it really tries to decrease the amount of admissions needed for pain crises... And I'm hearing you in that these admissions in general feel like a stressor.\" When the mother voiced a change goal — \"fewer crises, fewer hospital stays. That part I want for him, badly\" — the learner had a clear opening.\n- **Rationale:** The learner linked the medication's benefit to a stressor the mother cares about, and elicited some change-favourable language by problem-solving the nausea/timing. But the strongest change talk the mother offered (\"That part I want for him, badly\") was not reflected, affirmed, or elaborated — a missed opportunity to deepen momentum. The change talk that did emerge (\"I am willing to try that,\" \"I can work with this plan\") arose largely because the learner solved a logistical problem, not because they actively cultivated and strengthened the client's own reasons/desire. Competent with real gaps, so Good rather than Very good.\n- **Recommendations:** When the client states a desire, reflect and elaborate it rather than moving on — e.g., \"You want fewer crises for him so badly you can feel it. Tell me what a stretch without a hospital stay would mean for your family.\" This amplifies the client's own argument for change.\n\n### Softening Sustain Talk — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** To \"some days, honestly, I let him skip it,\" the learner responded \"I don't blame you. I can imagine that Jordan feels awful...\" then reframed toward the shared stressor rather than probing the skipping. Facing the cancer/fertility fears, the learner addressed them factually and pivoted to actionable problem-solving on nausea and timing.\n- **Rationale:** The learner consistently avoided deepening the status-quo case — never asked the mother to elaborate reasons not to give the medication, never dwelt on the burdens as barriers. Instead they redirected toward workable change (nighttime dosing, phone follow-up). Not a full 5 because \"I don't blame you [for letting him skip]\" mildly validated the status-quo behaviour rather than steering, but overall the handling was skillful and consistent.\n- **Recommendations:** Keep redirecting, but avoid endorsing the skip itself; acknowledge the feeling while holding the change frame — e.g., \"Mornings are impossible right now, and you're looking for a way this could actually work for him.\"\n\n### Partnership — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"let's make sure that Jordan's on the same page too... make sure that he feels like this is a good plan for him\"; \"let's follow up by phone. Let's make this as easy as possible for you\"; \"Maybe next time the three of us can have a conversation.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner repeatedly shared power — negotiated the follow-up modality to fit her life, invited the adolescent in as a decision-maker, and framed the plan as jointly built. They elicited her existing knowledge (\"Tell me everything that you've heard... and then share my understanding\") before advising. It stops short of 5 because the dosing solution was offered as the clinician's idea rather than drawn from her (\"tell me about what it would feel like if you gave it to him at nighttime\") — a lightly disguised suggestion rather than genuine co-generation of options.\n- **Recommendations:** Ask for the client's ideas first — \"What have you tried, or what do you think might make the mornings easier?\" — before offering your own, so the plan originates with her.\n\n### Empathy — 4/5 · Very good\n- **Evidence:** \"It feels like a big stressor in your life right now\"; \"I am running on empty\" met with \"I see you, and I hear you\"; \"it feels like a lot of conflicting things that people are saying, and I can imagine it feels really confusing.\"\n- **Rationale:** The learner tracked the mother's emotional state closely and reflected the felt experience, not just the facts — the exhaustion, the confusion, the sense of being unseen. The reflections were mostly accurate and the mother repeatedly confirmed them (\"that actually means something to hear\"). It falls short of 5 because the reflections stayed largely at the level the mother had already voiced; there were few complex reflections anticipating unstated meaning (e.g., the fear beneath the cancer worry, or the guilt of letting him skip), which is the hallmark of top-end empathy.\n- **Recommendations:** Reach for the meaning under the words — e.g., \"It sounds like part of what's so hard is being handed a medicine that hurts him now to protect a future you can't see yet.\" This anticipates rather than echoes.\n\n### MI core skills (OARS) — 3/5 · Good\n- **Evidence:** Open questions: \"tell me about what Jordan's experience has been like\"; \"Tell me everything that you've heard.\" Reflections: \"you're juggling with so much\"; \"it feels like a big stressor.\" Affirmation: implicit only. When directly asked for facts, the learner gave a somewhat disorganized information dump on cancer/fertility risk without seeking permission first.\n- **Rationale:** Good use of open questions and several accurate simple/complex reflections, with a reflection-heavy stance and little confrontation. But affirmation of the mother's strengths/efforts was thin (no explicit affirmation of her advocacy or juggling), no collecting summary linked her statements, and the risk information was delivered without an autonomy-supporting \"would it be okay if I share what I understand?\" ask — and was factually loose (\"might not actually be due to the hydroxyurea\"). Competent OARS with clear gaps places this at Good.\n- **Recommendations:** Ask permission before informing and affirm effort explicitly — e.g., \"You've clearly done a lot of homework on this, and you're fighting hard for him. Would it help if I laid out what the evidence actually shows on the cancer and fertility worries?\"\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — The learner built a genuinely collaborative, warm encounter: they opened non-defensively to a charged statement about racism and being unheard, reflected the mother's exhaustion and confusion accurately, negotiated a follow-up plan around her real constraints, and repeatedly worked to bring the adolescent in as a partner. Empathy and partnership were the clear high points, and sustain talk was handled without ever deepening the case against treatment.\n- **Priority gaps** — The strongest change talk (\"I want that for him, badly\") went un-elaborated; the dosing solution and information were clinician-generated rather than drawn from the client; risk information was given without seeking permission and was somewhat imprecise; and explicit affirmation and any collecting summary were missing.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. When the client voices desire or reason to change, stop and amplify it with a reflection before moving on.\n  2. Ask permission before giving information, and tighten the accuracy of what you share.\n  3. Elicit the client's own ideas for solving problems before offering your own suggestion.\n  4. Add at least one explicit affirmation of her strengths and a brief summary that links her statements toward the plan.",
