        "gradeId": "68802b80-23ce-4dbf-ac1d-6791be67d604",
        "rubricName": "Pediatric Hematology-Oncology — PROF1: Professional Behavior",
        "content": "## PROF1: Professional Behavior — Level 3 / 5 · Competent\nPediatric Hematology-Oncology milestone · levels 1–5, novice → expert (Dreyfus)\n\n**Assigned level:** 3 · Competent — the highest level fully demonstrated. Levels 4–5 turn in part on behaviors (coaching others, extending the role beyond patient care, intervening in others' lapses) the single encounter gave little or no opportunity to surface.\n\n**Level progression:** Levels 1–3 demonstrated; Level 4 partially demonstrated; Level 5 not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity).\n\n## Evidence by level\n\n### Level 1 · Novice — Demonstrated\nIdentifies expected professional behaviors and, implicitly, the triggers for lapses (a mistrustful parent invoking racial injustice, a demand for a straight answer). The learner opens with respect and does not become defensive.\n\"Monique, thank you so much for sharing your frustration with me... I would really love to hear about what Jordan's experience has been like.\"\n\n### Level 2 · Advanced beginner — Demonstrated\nDemonstrates professional behavior and takes accountability for the patient's care. The learner owns the therapeutic relationship and commits to follow-through.\n\"So let's say, let's try this, right? And then let's follow up maybe in a week and see... how it goes.\"\n\n### Level 3 · Competent — Demonstrated\nMaintains professionalism in a genuinely complex, emotionally charged, and racially fraught encounter, and fully engages in the patient's care while holding himself accountable. He stays honest under a direct challenge about cancer and fertility risk, and adapts the plan (nighttime dosing, phone follow-up, including the adolescent) to the family's real constraints.\n\"So I have to be honest with you in that I personally have not seen hydroxyurea itself cause cancer... that might not actually be due to the hydroxyurea itself.\"\n\"Yes, let's follow up by phone. Let's make this as easy as possible for you. I know you're juggling with so much.\"\n\n### Level 4 · Proficient — Partially demonstrated\nRecognizing triggers for professionalism lapses and exhibiting a sense of duty is partly shown: the learner clearly reads the trust deficit (\"nobody... listens to Black patients\") and responds with an explicit acknowledgment.\n\"Well, I see you, and I hear you, and I really appreciate you sharing this with me.\"\nHowever, the defining Level 4 behavior of *intervening to prevent lapses in self and others* — for instance, explicitly naming and addressing the medical system's failures the parent raised, or acknowledging the legitimacy of her mistrust as rooted in real inequities — was only lightly touched. The learner validated her feelings but did not directly engage the systemic/racial injustice she named, which was the central professionalism trigger of the case.\n\n### Level 5 · Expert — Not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity)\nLevel 5 requires modeling professional behavior while coaching others whose behavior falls short, and extending the role beyond patient care into community, specialty, and profession. No colleagues, trainees, or community context were present in this one-on-one parent encounter, so there was no occasion to demonstrate coaching or systems-level engagement. This does not count against the learner.\n\n## Rationale\nThe learner met every Level 3 behavior. He sustained professionalism through a confrontational, racially charged opening, stayed non-defensive, answered pointed questions honestly rather than glossing over risk, and fully engaged in the patient's care — building a shared plan around the family's real barriers and committing to follow-up. He held himself accountable (\"let's follow up... let's make this as easy as possible for you\") and recognized the adolescent's emerging autonomy (\"make sure that Jordan's on the same page too\"). This is competent professional behavior maintained under stress.\n\n## Why not the next level\nLevel 4 turns on recognizing situations that may trigger professionalism lapses and *intervening to prevent them in self and others*, plus a demonstrated sense of duty. The learner recognized the trust/racial-injustice trigger and validated it warmly, but stopped short of directly addressing the systemic distrust she voiced — he pivoted to the medication rather than naming the reality of her experience of being unheard in the medical system. That is the emerging-but-incomplete Level 4 behavior. Level 5's coaching and beyond-the-patient engagement had no opportunity to surface in this encounter.\n\n## Recommendations\nTo move toward Level 4, name and address the professionalism trigger head-on rather than only validating the emotion. When a parent opens with \"nobody in these places really listens to Black patients,\" a stronger response acknowledges the legitimacy of that mistrust directly — e.g., \"You're right that the medical system has failed Black families in real ways, and that history is one reason it's completely reasonable to question what I'm telling you. My job today is to earn your trust, not assume it.\" This intervenes on the systemic distrust as a documented driver of nonadherence and models accountability for the profession's failures, not just for the individual patient's plan. Continue the strengths already shown: honesty under pressure, adapting to family constraints, and including the adolescent in decisions.\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Maintained warm, non-defensive professionalism through a confrontational and racially fraught opening; answered hard questions about cancer and fertility risk honestly instead of deflecting; and engaged fully in the patient's care by tailoring dosing timing, follow-up modality, and adolescent involvement to the family's real life.\n- **Priority gaps** — Validated the parent's feeling of being unheard but did not directly engage the systemic racial injustice she named as the core professionalism trigger; that direct intervention is the threshold behavior for Level 4. Level 5 could not be assessed in a one-on-one encounter.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Name and address trust/equity triggers explicitly, not just the emotion behind them.\n  2. Continue answering high-stakes questions honestly and framing uncertainty plainly.\n  3. Keep building plans around the family's real constraints and the adolescent's autonomy.",
