        "gradeId": "da9009b0-9c8c-411e-a605-5c4357f05d93",
        "rubricName": "Pediatric Hematology-Oncology — PROF2: Ethical Principles",
        "content": "## PROF2: Ethical Principles — Level 2 / 5 · Advanced beginner\nPediatric Hematology-Oncology milestone · levels 1–5, novice → expert (Dreyfus)\n\n**Assigned level:** 2 · Advanced beginner — the highest level whose behaviors are fully demonstrated; higher levels (complex ethical analysis, formal ethics resources) never arose in this encounter, so the ceiling reflects the scenario, not solely a learner shortfall.\n\n**Level progression:** Levels 1–2 demonstrated; Level 3 partially demonstrated; Levels 4–5 not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity).\n\n## Evidence by level\n### Level 1 · Novice — Demonstrated\nThe learner shows working knowledge of the ethical principles underlying informed disclosure and adolescent involvement in decision-making. He commits to truthful, non-coercive information sharing about hydroxyurea's benefits and risks: \"So I have to be honest with you...\" and he distinguishes association from causation regarding cancer and fertility risk. He also invokes the principle of the developing adolescent's voice: \"let's make sure that Jordan's on the same page too.\"\n\n### Level 2 · Advanced beginner — Demonstrated\nThe learner applies these principles fluently in a common clinical situation — a parent questioning adherence and considering stopping therapy. He honors autonomy without abandoning beneficence, working toward a shared plan rather than dictating one: \"let's try this... let's follow up maybe in a week and see... let's make sure that Jordan's on the same page.\" He anticipates the emerging assent of a 13-year-old: \"next time the three of us can have a conversation so that we can include him in this.\" He accommodates barriers (phone follow-up) as a matter of equitable, patient-centered care. These are textbook applications of consent/assent and autonomy in an everyday encounter.\n\n### Level 3 · Competent — Partially demonstrated\nThe character opens with a charged structural concern — \"Nobody in these places really listens to Black patients\" — which introduces a potential ethical dimension of trust, equity, and possible controversy. The learner responds empathically (\"I see you, and I hear you\") and partially defuses conflict, but he does not analyze or explicitly name the underlying ethical tension (mistrust rooted in racism, the risk of undertreatment). He handles the adherence conflict and the parent's decisional ambivalence competently, but he does not frame the situation in explicit ethical terms, nor does he identify any need for outside help. Analysis of the complex situation using ethical principles is only implicit, so this level is not fully met. There was a real opportunity here that was only partly seized.\n\n### Level 4 · Proficient — Not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity)\nNothing in this single outpatient adherence conversation called for an ethics consultation, literature review, or risk-management/legal input. The situation did not rise to a formal ethical dilemma requiring such resources, so this behavior could not be surfaced. This does not count against the learner.\n\n### Level 5 · Expert — Not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity)\nBeing called upon by others to consult on complex dilemmas, and identifying system-level factors, cannot be shown in a single two-person encounter. The parent did name a system-level issue (mistrust of the medical system by Black patients), which the learner might have engaged more explicitly, but the consultative and system-change behaviors of Level 5 had no venue here.\n\n## Rationale\nThe learner clearly holds the ethical knowledge of Level 1 and applies it well in a common situation at Level 2: he is honest about risks and benefits, corrects a misconception without dismissing it, respects parental autonomy while advocating for beneficial therapy, and repeatedly moves to include the adolescent's assent — a genuine, principled application of consent/assent ethics. That is the highest level fully demonstrated.\n\n## Why not the next level\nLevel 3 requires explicitly analyzing a complex situation through ethical principles to address conflict or controversy, and seeking help when needed. The scenario handed the learner exactly such an opening — the parent's statement about racism and mistrust, and her ambivalence about long-term therapy. The learner responded warmly and rebuilt trust, but never named or analyzed the ethical tension (equity, informed refusal, the balance of a minor's developing autonomy against parental decisions to skip doses). Because that analytic, explicitly-ethical framing was possible but not delivered, Level 3 is only partially met.\n\n## Recommendations\n- When a family names structural mistrust, engage it explicitly as an ethical and equity issue rather than only offering empathy — e.g., \"You're right that Black families have too often been dismissed by medicine, and that history is real; part of my job is to earn your trust by being straight with you, including when I don't know something.\"\n- Name the ethical tension aloud when a parent skips doses of a beneficial, non-emergent therapy for a minor: acknowledge her autonomy as guardian while framing Jordan's own developing right to be informed and to assent — \"We're balancing your judgment as his mom, what the medicine can do for him, and Jordan's growing right to have a say.\"\n- When misconceptions about serious risks (cancer, fertility) arise, ground the reassurance in the evidence base and offer to share written information — this moves toward the resource-use expected at higher levels.\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Excellent rapport repair and empathy; honest, non-coercive risk communication that corrected a causation misconception; consistent, principled inclusion of the adolescent's assent and practical accommodation of the family's barriers.\n- **Priority gaps** — The learner never explicitly engaged the ethical/equity dimension the parent raised (mistrust of medicine, structural bias) or named the autonomy/beneficence tension in the adherence decision. Higher milestone levels (formal ethics resources, consultative role, system-level advocacy) had no occasion to appear in this encounter.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Explicitly name and address equity/mistrust as an ethical issue when a family raises it, not with empathy alone.\n  2. Articulate the ethical framework aloud (parental authority, child's best interest, adolescent assent) when adherence conflicts arise.\n  3. Anchor risk reassurance in evidence and offer written or reputable resources to support informed decision-making.",
